WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:05.300
You know, usually when we talk about a medical diagnosis, there's this expectation of, like, total clinical precision.

00:05.460 --> 00:06.140
Oh, yeah, absolutely.

00:06.240 --> 00:12.740
I mean, you break your arm, the x-ray shows that jagged white line, and the doctor just points at the film and says, there's the problem.

00:13.040 --> 00:15.660
Right. It's broken or not broken. Very binary.

00:15.920 --> 00:20.260
Exactly. It's clean, it's visible, and we just love that kind of categorization.

00:21.020 --> 00:25.400
But when we look at the current civilizational moment we're in right now...

00:25.400 --> 00:26.540
The intelligence explosion.

00:26.540 --> 00:31.680
Yes, this massive, undeniable intelligence explosion happening all around us with AI.

00:32.440 --> 00:38.060
Well, our collective x-ray machine might actually be pointing at the wrong patient entirely.

00:38.420 --> 00:43.040
It's so true. We are experiencing a global misdiagnosis right now.

00:43.120 --> 00:45.200
A misdiagnosis on a massive scale.

00:45.300 --> 00:55.340
Yeah, because every headline, every tech analysis you read, every regulatory framework, they're all hyper-focused on generative AI and large language models.

00:55.340 --> 00:56.720
Right, the models themselves.

00:56.840 --> 01:01.660
Exactly. We point at the server farms running these massive parameter models, and we just say, there it is.

01:01.940 --> 01:03.320
There is the source of the intelligence.

01:03.680 --> 01:09.740
Which brings us to our mission for this deep dive, because today we are looking directly at you, the learner.

01:09.980 --> 01:10.280
Yes.

01:10.520 --> 01:16.480
Because the way you and I, and basically the rest of the world, have been understanding this huge technological leap,

01:16.480 --> 01:19.260
well, it is about to be turned upside down.

01:19.360 --> 01:20.180
Completely upside down.

01:20.200 --> 01:29.540
We are examining a brand new paper published literally today, May 14, 2026, by an author writing under the name Flyxion.

01:29.980 --> 01:31.860
And the title alone is just a labyrinth.

01:31.940 --> 01:32.880
It really is.

01:32.880 --> 01:41.620
It's titled, Globally Persistent Recomposable Thought, GitHub, The Intelligence Explosion, and the Admissibility Geometry of Collective Cognition.

01:41.920 --> 01:45.560
It is a dense, multi-layered, and frankly, radical thesis.

01:45.780 --> 01:46.620
Very radical.

01:47.020 --> 01:53.860
Flyxion's core argument is that the generative AI models we are all obsessing over, well, they are not the engine of the intelligence explosion.

01:53.880 --> 01:55.120
Reid, they aren't the engine.

01:55.280 --> 01:56.840
No, they are merely the accelerant.

01:56.920 --> 01:57.440
Wow.

01:57.440 --> 02:04.340
The actual fuel, the foundational structural substrate that made this entire era possible, was built two decades earlier.

02:04.540 --> 02:05.740
Okay, two decades ago.

02:05.780 --> 02:06.020
Yes.

02:06.420 --> 02:10.200
It's the open source ecosystem, operationalized globally by GitHub.

02:10.440 --> 02:11.700
Okay, let's unpack this.

02:12.360 --> 02:19.120
Because saying GitHub is the actual intelligence explosion feels, honestly, incredibly counterintuitive.

02:19.680 --> 02:20.080
Oh, I know.

02:20.080 --> 02:25.040
I mean, most people just think of it as, like, a Google Drive for programmers, just a place to store files.

02:25.180 --> 02:27.360
Right, a giant digital filing cabinet.

02:27.580 --> 02:28.100
Exactly.

02:28.480 --> 02:37.400
So to understand what Flyxion means by this substrate, we need to look at the mathematical factorization the paper uses to describe AI capability.

02:37.880 --> 02:43.560
Yeah, so the traditional narrative models AI capability purely as a function of the model itself.

02:43.760 --> 02:44.540
Just with the parameters.

02:44.800 --> 02:44.960
Right.

02:45.080 --> 02:49.440
The more parameters you add, the more compute you throw at it, you know, the smarter it gets.

02:49.440 --> 02:50.840
The classic stealing laws.

02:51.020 --> 02:51.340
Exactly.

02:51.960 --> 02:55.260
But Flyxion argues this equation is missing its most critical variable.

02:55.260 --> 03:03.880
The paper expresses capability at time t as a joint function of the model at time t and the graph of open source repositories at time t.

03:04.080 --> 03:06.340
So it's a joint function, both things at once.

03:06.340 --> 03:10.620
Yes, that vast interconnected graph of human problem solving.

03:10.980 --> 03:11.820
That is the substrate.

03:12.180 --> 03:15.500
And the paper runs a really fascinating thought experiment here.

03:15.720 --> 03:21.500
It argues that if you held that open source graph fixed at its pre-2005 state.

03:21.500 --> 03:25.100
Before Git and GitHub revolutionized how we share code.

03:25.220 --> 03:25.440
Right.

03:25.540 --> 03:26.300
Before all of that.

03:26.460 --> 03:35.900
If you kept the code sharing static and you only scaled up the AI models to their current massive sizes, you would get a system with dramatically lower capabilities.

03:36.120 --> 03:36.740
Dramatically lower.

03:36.860 --> 03:39.880
So the intelligence explosion isn't just the AI getting bigger.

03:40.020 --> 03:44.380
It's the joint entangled growth of the AI and the repository graph.

03:44.380 --> 03:49.380
What's fascinating here is how this forces us to fundamentally redefine intelligence.

03:49.500 --> 03:50.160
Like who so?

03:50.320 --> 03:54.120
Well, we are so used to thinking of intelligence as inference sufficiency.

03:54.380 --> 03:56.000
Like how fast it can answer a question.

03:56.280 --> 03:56.560
Right.

03:57.060 --> 04:03.180
How fast an isolated agent, whether that's a human brain or an AI model, can process a prompt and spit out an answer.

04:03.260 --> 04:04.020
Sure, that makes sense.

04:04.020 --> 04:13.180
But Flyxion redefines intelligence as the persistence, the replayability, and the recomposability of developmental trajectories across a collective network.

04:13.360 --> 04:14.940
Okay, that's a lot of big words.

04:15.320 --> 04:15.780
It is.

04:16.200 --> 04:20.020
But under this definition, GitHub isn't just a storage facility.

04:20.480 --> 04:29.800
It is active, intelligent infrastructure because it captures and preserves the intermediate cognitive states of millions of human beings.

04:30.420 --> 04:32.940
Okay, I have to push back a little on this premise, though.

04:32.940 --> 04:33.600
Go for it.

04:33.600 --> 04:40.340
Doesn't this framework kind of diminish the undeniable technical genius of large language models?

04:40.700 --> 04:44.280
I mean, the transformer architecture itself was a massive breakthrough.

04:44.320 --> 04:45.180
It was a massive breakthrough.

04:45.360 --> 04:45.720
Absolutely.

04:46.040 --> 04:50.520
So to wrap my head around this, I keep visualizing LLMs as the world's greatest librarians.

04:50.780 --> 04:51.480
I like that analogy.

04:51.620 --> 04:56.720
Yeah, like they can find anything, synthesize anything, and speak literally any language fluently.

04:57.000 --> 04:57.240
Right.

04:57.240 --> 04:57.800
Right.

04:57.800 --> 05:03.780
But even the greatest librarian in the universe is completely useless if they are standing in an empty room.

05:03.860 --> 05:04.240
Exactly.

05:04.440 --> 05:06.080
They need the library of Alexandria.

05:06.480 --> 05:07.480
They need the books.

05:07.480 --> 05:12.060
And more importantly, according to this paper, they need the rough drafts of those books.

05:12.060 --> 05:16.840
The librarian analogy works perfectly to illustrate the gap between the engine and the substrate.

05:17.340 --> 05:28.420
Because to really grasp the magnitude of the library we've built, we have to remember how brutally difficult it was to build software before distributed version control was normalized.

05:28.420 --> 05:31.280
Oh, the pre-GitHub dark ages.

05:31.480 --> 05:32.380
The dark ages, yes.

05:32.840 --> 05:35.420
They were defined by heavy institutional silos.

05:35.820 --> 05:37.780
I remember hearing stories about this.

05:38.140 --> 05:45.200
Yeah, I mean, if a developer at a university solved a complex networking problem, that solution just lived on a private hard drive.

05:45.440 --> 05:47.300
Or maybe a floppy disk back in the day.

05:47.520 --> 05:47.780
Right.

05:48.100 --> 05:53.800
Or maybe it got zicked up into a tarball and hosted on some obscure FTP mirror that literally nobody knew about.

05:53.960 --> 05:55.040
Hidden away entirely.

05:55.300 --> 05:56.840
It was hidden in mailing list archives.

05:57.060 --> 05:57.260
Yeah.

05:57.260 --> 05:59.100
Or locked behind academic paywalls.

05:59.120 --> 06:03.160
So the friction to actually reuse someone else's code was just astronomical.

06:03.760 --> 06:04.240
Gastronomical.

06:04.240 --> 06:10.120
And Flyxion defines this mathematically as recombination friction, denoted by the Greek letter rho.

06:10.740 --> 06:10.980
Yes.

06:11.340 --> 06:16.960
So if I wanted to use your code back in, say, 2003, I had to manually download it.

06:17.040 --> 06:19.160
And figure out my undocumented dependencies.

06:19.660 --> 06:19.940
Right.

06:20.260 --> 06:24.400
Guess what operating system you were using, patch all the incompatibilities by hand,

06:24.400 --> 06:27.460
and then I just have to maintain my own local poppy forever.

06:27.460 --> 06:32.140
Because if I updated my code, you had no automatic way to sync those changes.

06:32.600 --> 06:34.580
Knowledge transfer was just so slow.

06:35.020 --> 06:35.840
It was lossy.

06:36.180 --> 06:42.340
And it heavily favored massive corporations that could afford to just centralize all their developers in one building.

06:42.340 --> 06:42.900
Exactly.

06:43.380 --> 06:46.520
But GitHub collapsed that recombination friction.

06:46.540 --> 06:47.340
Yeah, it just destroyed it.

06:47.440 --> 06:51.780
It introduced what the paper calls composability monotonicity.

06:52.320 --> 06:53.880
Composability monotonicity.

06:53.920 --> 06:54.200
Yes.

06:54.340 --> 06:54.560
Yeah.

06:54.560 --> 07:00.240
By standardizing how dependencies are tracked, making forking literally a one-click operation.

07:00.500 --> 07:01.720
Just click a button and it's yours?

07:01.980 --> 07:02.220
Right.

07:02.720 --> 07:11.820
And by integrating issue resolution directly into the code base, the platform drove that friction variable down toward a near-constant baseline.

07:11.980 --> 07:15.300
And the mathematical proof sketch in the paper actually demonstrates this.

07:15.300 --> 07:23.600
It shows that as recombination friction approaches zero, the number of reachable composite software systems you can build grows exponentially.

07:23.860 --> 07:24.660
It's an exponential curve.

07:24.840 --> 07:27.200
So it wasn't just a modest improvement in workflow.

07:27.420 --> 07:31.740
It was a structural collapse in friction that triggered a combinatorial explosion.

07:31.940 --> 07:32.960
A total explosion.

07:33.840 --> 07:41.320
Every piece of modern AI infrastructure we rely on today, the training pipelines, the tensor libraries, the tokenizers.

07:41.480 --> 07:42.940
None of it was built in isolation.

07:43.200 --> 07:43.760
None of it.

07:43.760 --> 07:49.320
It emerged from this ultra-dense, recursively-improving open-source ecosystem.

07:49.660 --> 07:50.060
Wow.

07:50.300 --> 07:55.400
A modern foundation model is, quite literally, a stitched-together graph of these repositories.

07:56.000 --> 07:59.840
It is the emergent output of reduced recombination friction.

08:00.360 --> 08:07.780
Okay, so if GitHub built this planetary-scale library and drove the friction of reading and writing code to zero, we have to ask a big question.

08:08.020 --> 08:08.400
What's that?

08:08.620 --> 08:10.980
What exactly is sitting on the shelves of this library?

08:10.980 --> 08:15.160
Because Flyxion argues it is not what we traditionally think of as software.

08:15.360 --> 08:16.000
No, it's not.

08:16.140 --> 08:20.100
And this requires a total paradigm shift in how we view code itself.

08:20.300 --> 08:21.000
It really does.

08:21.440 --> 08:24.660
The conventional view is that a software repository is an artifact.

08:25.040 --> 08:26.340
An artifact, like a relic.

08:26.400 --> 08:27.380
Like a finished product.

08:27.580 --> 08:34.140
It is a static, finished information object, a collection of files that you execute to run a program.

08:34.440 --> 08:34.780
Okay.

08:34.780 --> 08:37.580
But Flyxion completely rejects this ontology.

08:38.640 --> 08:41.100
The formal expression in the paper is uncompromising.

08:41.780 --> 08:46.460
It says the artifact of a repository does not equal the trajectory of a repository.

08:46.800 --> 08:47.040
Okay.

08:47.160 --> 08:48.860
The artifact does not equal the trajectory.

08:49.020 --> 08:49.200
Right.

08:49.340 --> 08:53.720
Older version control systems or those old FTP servers, they only preserve the artifact.

08:53.980 --> 08:56.840
You just downloaded the final polished file.

08:56.960 --> 08:57.340
Exactly.

08:57.340 --> 08:59.680
But GitHub preserves the trajectory.

09:00.360 --> 09:06.600
It captures every pull request, every debate in the issue tracker, the bugs, the abandoned branches, the patches.

09:06.860 --> 09:07.560
It's all there.

09:07.680 --> 09:12.280
It exposes the developmental geometry that final polished code actively conceals.

09:12.540 --> 09:14.980
Think about the implications of this for learning, though.

09:15.120 --> 09:15.360
Right.

09:15.360 --> 09:18.440
Because if you only see an artifact, you only know the final state.

09:18.960 --> 09:29.060
But a trajectory is a compressed historical record of how a system moved through a highly complex semantic configuration space to arrive at that state.

09:29.360 --> 09:31.380
It maps the human decision-making process.

09:31.580 --> 09:31.820
Yeah.

09:31.920 --> 09:34.960
This makes me think of, like, a high-level math class.

09:35.020 --> 09:36.280
Oh, that's a great way to look at it.

09:36.440 --> 09:41.660
If you look in a textbook, you see a perfectly formatted, elegant mathematical proof.

09:41.780 --> 09:42.760
That is the artifact.

09:42.760 --> 09:48.080
It's clean, but it doesn't teach you how the mathematician actually invented it.

09:48.300 --> 09:48.700
Not at all.

09:48.780 --> 09:58.740
But if you walk into the professor's office and look at their chalkboard, it's covered in erased mistakes, crossed-out dead ends, margin notes, and arrows pointing to different logical pathways.

09:59.000 --> 09:59.560
It's messy.

09:59.680 --> 10:01.540
That messy chalkboard is the trajectory.

10:01.780 --> 10:03.380
I love that chalkboard analogy.

10:03.620 --> 10:07.140
But here is where my ML understanding hits a wall, I have to admit.

10:07.640 --> 10:08.680
Okay, where are you stuck?

10:08.680 --> 10:12.780
Why are those mistakes mathematically valuable for an AI?

10:13.220 --> 10:13.700
Ah.

10:14.040 --> 10:18.780
Like, why is seeing the messy chalkboard computationally better than just reading the clean textbook?

10:19.700 --> 10:26.140
Shouldn't we want to train AI purely on perfect functioning code so it doesn't learn human errors?

10:26.500 --> 10:27.320
It's a great question.

10:27.740 --> 10:31.160
It comes down to a mechanism the paper calls semantic replay.

10:31.520 --> 10:32.460
Semantic replay.

10:32.580 --> 10:32.760
Right.

10:32.760 --> 10:36.440
When a developer forks a repository, they aren't just copying a static file.

10:36.560 --> 10:37.120
They aren't.

10:37.260 --> 10:39.440
No, because copying only replicates the artifact.

10:40.040 --> 10:41.400
Forking is a replay operation.

10:41.480 --> 10:42.160
A replay operation.

10:42.260 --> 10:42.400
Okay.

10:42.500 --> 10:48.900
The developer takes the entire developmental trace of that project and re-executes it under new initial conditions.

10:49.100 --> 10:50.900
So they are running history forward again.

10:51.080 --> 10:51.500
Exactly.

10:51.500 --> 10:56.360
Maybe they are porting it to a new operating system or swapping out a core dependency.

10:57.120 --> 11:04.140
They are replaying the trajectory to see if the core idea, the semantic invariant, survives the new environment.

11:04.460 --> 11:06.880
So GitHub isn't a static storage drive at all.

11:06.960 --> 11:09.860
It is a partially continuous evolutionary system.

11:10.100 --> 11:11.280
That's exactly what it is.

11:11.680 --> 11:15.820
And evolutionary systems require variation to progress, right?

11:15.860 --> 11:16.040
Yeah.

11:16.340 --> 11:18.420
And variation inherently requires failure.

11:18.520 --> 11:18.740
Right.

11:19.000 --> 11:19.440
Mutation.

11:19.440 --> 11:27.300
If an AI model only ever ingested perfect, finished artifacts, it would only know what a functional system looks like in a vacuum.

11:27.520 --> 11:28.800
Because it only saw the textbook.

11:29.220 --> 11:29.580
Exactly.

11:29.960 --> 11:32.020
It would know how to navigate out of a broken state.

11:32.320 --> 11:32.720
Wow.

11:32.900 --> 11:42.200
By ingesting the trajectory, including the off-by-one errors, the failed architectural choices, the syntax bugs, the AI learns the geometry of problem solving.

11:42.300 --> 11:43.500
It learns how to solve problems.

11:43.500 --> 11:54.620
It learns how a system becomes functional because it has mapped millions of recorded instances of humans navigating from a broken state to a working state.

11:54.720 --> 11:54.860
Okay.

11:54.960 --> 11:56.700
Let's make this really concrete for the listener.

11:56.780 --> 11:57.100
Good idea.

11:57.440 --> 12:03.320
Imagine a human developer trying to write a Python script for a custom web scraper, right?

12:03.320 --> 12:07.100
And they keep failing because they are hitting rate limits on the server.

12:07.340 --> 12:08.500
A very common problem.

12:08.640 --> 12:09.240
Super common.

12:09.480 --> 12:09.640
Yeah.

12:09.660 --> 12:12.040
So they push a commit that says added sleep timer.

12:12.280 --> 12:13.280
It still fails.

12:13.540 --> 12:16.540
They push another commit trying rotating proxies.

12:16.920 --> 12:17.840
It fails.

12:17.980 --> 12:18.840
The code breaks.

12:19.080 --> 12:24.080
They leave a frustrated comment in the issue tracker and they just abandon the project entirely.

12:24.200 --> 12:24.880
They just give up.

12:25.020 --> 12:25.260
Right.

12:25.260 --> 12:28.520
But then, a year later, someone else forks it.

12:28.600 --> 12:29.360
They pick up the debris?

12:29.760 --> 12:29.960
Yeah.

12:30.160 --> 12:31.040
They read the history.

12:31.320 --> 12:33.280
They realize the header formatting is wrong.

12:33.360 --> 12:34.020
They fix it.

12:34.140 --> 12:36.060
And suddenly, the scraper works perfectly.

12:36.220 --> 12:36.880
So beautiful.

12:37.320 --> 12:40.900
So when an AI reads that repository, it isn't just learning how to scrape a website.

12:40.900 --> 12:50.500
It is learning the exact sequence of human frustration, the false hypotheses, and the eventual architectural pivot that solved the problem.

12:50.620 --> 12:52.580
It is learning the shape of the solution.

12:52.820 --> 12:53.980
The shape of the solution.

12:53.980 --> 12:55.500
That's a great way to phrase it.

12:55.760 --> 13:02.040
And that specific sequence, the false hypotheses, the pivot, the resolution, is the developmental geometry.

13:02.540 --> 13:10.580
And because GitHub captures this globally, the AI learns to generalize that geometry across entirely different domains of programming.

13:10.800 --> 13:11.220
Absolutely.

13:11.640 --> 13:15.740
But this introduces a massive sociological puzzle.

13:15.980 --> 13:16.420
Which is?

13:16.420 --> 13:24.120
Why did millions of fiercely competitive human beings suddenly decide to do all their messy, mistake-ridden thinking in public?

13:24.900 --> 13:26.300
It's wild when you think about it.

13:26.480 --> 13:30.220
Historically, that is the exact opposite of how human institutions operate.

13:30.420 --> 13:31.400
We hide our mistakes.

13:31.480 --> 13:31.680
Always.

13:31.680 --> 13:38.800
And Flyxion dedicates a major portion of the paper to this epistemic economy, detailing what they call the incentive inversion.

13:39.020 --> 13:40.060
The incentive inversion.

13:40.200 --> 13:40.340
Right.

13:40.540 --> 13:47.300
To understand the scale of this shift, we have to look at the Nash equilibrium of software development before this substrate existed.

13:47.420 --> 13:49.300
Okay, let's look at academia and industry.

13:49.560 --> 13:52.500
They were both heavily optimized around hoarding knowledge, right?

13:52.500 --> 13:53.060
Oh, completely.

13:53.060 --> 13:58.240
In academia, publishing incomplete or buggy work was basically professional suicide.

13:58.560 --> 14:00.540
Because journal slots were so stares.

14:01.040 --> 14:01.300
Yes.

14:02.220 --> 14:09.240
The peer review process systematically selected for clean, positive outcomes and perfect retrospective coherence.

14:09.680 --> 14:15.540
So if a researcher wrote five failed implementations of an algorithm before finally getting the math to work...

14:15.540 --> 14:16.680
They hid the five failures.

14:16.800 --> 14:17.620
They just hid them.

14:17.620 --> 14:17.980
Yep.

14:18.160 --> 14:24.280
All that productive cognitive work, all of that valuable trajectory data just vanished onto private hard drives.

14:24.400 --> 14:25.960
And the corporate world was identical.

14:26.260 --> 14:27.620
It was driven by financial imperatives.

14:28.480 --> 14:33.300
Proprietary tooling, closed research pipelines, isolated engineering cultures.

14:33.540 --> 14:36.960
Because secrecy was viewed as the ultimate competitive advantage.

14:37.300 --> 14:39.620
You did not show your competitors your messy chalkboard.

14:40.460 --> 14:40.740
Never.

14:41.020 --> 14:44.080
So how did GitHub cause a Nash equilibrium shift?

14:44.080 --> 14:47.700
Well, we can break it down using the payoff matrix Flyxion provides.

14:48.540 --> 14:54.780
The matrix contrasts the private value of keeping a code-based secret against the public value of open-sourcing it.

14:54.920 --> 14:55.080
Okay.

14:56.060 --> 15:01.140
Pre-GitHub, the private value almost always dominated because the friction to share was too high.

15:01.360 --> 15:05.000
And the rewards for sharing were, frankly, negligible.

15:05.100 --> 15:05.300
Right.

15:05.360 --> 15:06.000
There was no point.

15:06.000 --> 15:14.900
But GitHub fundamentally altered the equation for public value by introducing powerful new social and economic primitives.

15:15.180 --> 15:16.340
Like the stars and forks.

15:16.420 --> 15:16.820
Exactly.

15:17.380 --> 15:20.640
It added reputation signals like stars, forks, and watchers.

15:20.860 --> 15:24.980
It created the highest bandwidth talent discovery market in human history.

15:25.180 --> 15:26.100
That makes a lot of sense.

15:26.280 --> 15:33.240
And it formalized community maintenance value where an external developer might fix your bugs for free simply because they rely on your tool.

15:33.240 --> 15:38.080
So the repository essentially became an executable appendix for academic researchers.

15:38.320 --> 15:39.360
Executable appendix.

15:39.420 --> 15:39.900
I like that.

15:39.980 --> 15:50.480
Because in complex fields like machine learning today, publishing a paper without the accompanying GitHub repository is increasingly viewed as just incomplete science.

15:50.680 --> 15:51.940
You'll get laughed out of the room.

15:52.020 --> 15:52.200
Right.

15:52.360 --> 15:54.880
You aren't just claiming a theoretical result anymore.

15:55.280 --> 16:01.660
You are required to provide the exact, verifiable, computational machinery that generated that result.

16:01.660 --> 16:04.660
It became a mechanism for epistemic credibility.

16:05.000 --> 16:12.240
And for software engineers, their GitHub profile evolved into a dynamic portfolio that is infinitely more expressive than a static resume.

16:12.460 --> 16:16.220
So a technical recruiter doesn't just see what languages you know.

16:16.680 --> 16:18.480
They can see your architectural taste.

16:18.560 --> 16:20.480
Your discipline in writing documentation.

16:20.900 --> 16:25.020
And how gracefully you handle technical disagreements in a pull request thread.

16:25.200 --> 16:26.100
That's huge.

16:26.100 --> 16:26.660
It is.

16:27.120 --> 16:33.300
Publishing open source code transformed from an act of altruism into an economically actionable necessity.

16:33.520 --> 16:36.700
Which leads to one of the most counterintuitive concepts in the paper.

16:37.340 --> 16:39.100
The utilization of cognitive debris.

16:39.760 --> 16:40.660
Cognitive debris.

16:40.800 --> 16:46.100
Because these incentives inverted so sharply, developers just started publishing absolutely everything.

16:46.940 --> 16:49.080
That abandoned web scraper we talked about.

16:49.400 --> 16:51.040
A buggy rendering engine.

16:51.560 --> 16:54.200
A half-finished experiment with neural networks.

16:54.200 --> 16:57.960
20 years ago, all of that would have been deleted to save disk space.

16:58.060 --> 16:59.980
Just dragged straight to the trash.

17:00.400 --> 17:03.140
But now, it sits permanently on GitHub.

17:03.640 --> 17:08.800
And Flyxion argues that this cognitive debris is the secret weapon of the substrate.

17:09.080 --> 17:09.920
The secret weapon.

17:10.220 --> 17:15.260
Yes, because an evolutionary system cannot predict which variation will be adaptive in the future.

17:15.380 --> 17:15.600
Right.

17:15.660 --> 17:16.900
You don't know it's going to be useful.

17:16.900 --> 17:25.640
By externalizing cognitive debris, instead of discarding it, the ecosystem maintains a massive reservoir of latent potential.

17:25.640 --> 17:35.660
So, someone on another continent can fork an abandoned 10-year-old project, extract a single mathematical subroutine that happens to solve a modern problem.

17:35.760 --> 17:37.560
And build a global standard out of it.

17:37.600 --> 17:38.040
Exactly.

17:38.500 --> 17:41.640
So, failure itself became a recursively reusable infrastructure.

17:42.520 --> 17:43.280
Beautifully said.

17:43.280 --> 17:46.660
So, what does this all mean on a macro, corporate scale?

17:46.860 --> 17:58.240
Because it really explains why the most fiercely competitive megacorporations on Earth, the Googles, the Metas, the Microsofts, are routinely open-sourcing their core AI frameworks.

17:58.400 --> 17:59.640
Look at PyTorch or TensorFlow.

17:59.640 --> 18:00.400
Right.

18:00.840 --> 18:15.880
The reputational value, the ability to attract the top 1% of engineering talent, and the immense power of setting the de facto industry standard, it completely eclipses the traditional, outdated strategy of keeping the source code locked in a corporate vault.

18:16.120 --> 18:18.680
The equilibrium became totally self-reinforcing.

18:19.100 --> 18:26.600
Once enough major players participate in the open source substrate, the reputational penalty for not participating becomes economically fatal.

18:26.720 --> 18:27.620
You just can't compete.

18:27.620 --> 18:38.280
Exactly. Through these aligned incentives, humanity inadvertently tricked itself into constructing a globally accessible planetary-scale working memory.

18:38.520 --> 18:49.800
Okay, we've established the social mechanics of why humans built this massive, chaotic library filled with both brilliant architectural masterpieces and broken cognitive debris.

18:49.920 --> 18:51.020
Yes, we have the library.

18:51.200 --> 18:54.060
But here is where my brain starts to melt a little bit.

18:54.160 --> 18:54.540
Uh-oh.

18:54.540 --> 18:59.060
How does this cognitive debris actually hold stable meaning?

18:59.360 --> 18:59.740
Ah.

18:59.960 --> 19:09.000
Because how can an AI possibly extract coherent intelligence from a substrate that is literally filled with broken stochastic noise?

19:09.280 --> 19:10.400
It's a profound question.

19:10.640 --> 19:13.840
And to prove this, Flyxion does something wildly unexpected.

19:14.060 --> 19:14.860
Very unexpected.

19:15.120 --> 19:18.500
They don't use Python or C++ as their model organism.

19:18.600 --> 19:19.300
No, they don't.

19:19.300 --> 19:23.900
They use a deliberately adversarial, incredibly obscure programming language.

19:24.000 --> 19:26.540
Yes, an esoteric programming language, or esolang.

19:26.720 --> 19:26.860
Yeah.

19:26.960 --> 19:28.720
And this one is called, well, it's pronounced in misis.

19:28.860 --> 19:34.640
It was created in 2012 as a randomized derivative of the notoriously difficult language brain fact.

19:35.380 --> 19:42.540
And I know this section of the paper is mathematically dense, but it isolates the philosophical core of how meaning survives chaos.

19:42.640 --> 19:43.440
It really does.

19:43.440 --> 19:50.760
And I really need to break down just how adversarial this language is for you listening, because it violates every rule of how we think computers work.

19:50.840 --> 19:51.680
Yeah, every single rule.

19:51.800 --> 19:57.800
In a normal programming language, if you write a plus sign, the program deterministically adds one to a value.

19:58.140 --> 20:00.720
If you write a minus sign, it subtracts one.

20:01.100 --> 20:01.860
You are in control.

20:02.000 --> 20:02.880
Very deterministic.

20:02.880 --> 20:08.060
But in MBSEF, the arithmetic and movement operators are entirely non-deterministic.

20:08.200 --> 20:08.800
They're randomized.

20:09.200 --> 20:09.380
Right.

20:09.460 --> 20:15.180
If you write a plus or a minus, the runtime engine flips a coin and randomly chooses whether to add or subtract.

20:15.400 --> 20:16.260
It's insane.

20:16.480 --> 20:20.120
If you tell the memory pointer to move left or right, it randomly chooses the direction.

20:20.500 --> 20:23.480
The syntax is completely severed from the operational behavior.

20:23.640 --> 20:25.760
It is pure stochastic chaos.

20:25.900 --> 20:26.460
Pure chaos.

20:26.460 --> 20:38.000
So my immediate question reading this was, why on earth would a paper about the global AI intelligence explosion use a joke programming language where the steering wheel randomly spins on its own?

20:38.520 --> 20:39.320
Well, think about it.

20:39.600 --> 20:46.940
Conventional programming languages are designed to aggressively minimize the friction between human intent and machine execution.

20:47.080 --> 20:48.060
They try to be predictable.

20:48.400 --> 20:48.900
Exactly.

20:48.900 --> 20:56.600
They provide strict deterministic control flow to mask the underlying unreliability and entropy of the physical universe.

20:57.620 --> 21:01.720
But an esoteric language like AMBUNA strips away all of that protective scaffolding.

21:02.080 --> 21:06.540
It forces the programmer and the theorist to confront a foundational question.

21:06.660 --> 21:07.120
Which is?

21:07.240 --> 21:16.200
What is the irreducible structural minimum required for coherent computation to survive in a deeply noisy, fundamentally unreliable environment?

21:16.480 --> 21:16.880
Wow.

21:16.880 --> 21:19.700
And the paper actually provides a mathematical proof for this.

21:19.920 --> 21:24.180
It demonstrates that the single invariant that survives this random drift is parity.

21:24.500 --> 21:24.860
Parity?

21:25.000 --> 21:28.500
The even or odd relationship of the positions on the data tape?

21:28.640 --> 21:28.900
Yes.

21:29.400 --> 21:34.800
If we look at the formal lemma in the paper, it proves that parity is strictly preserved under symmetric random walks.

21:35.120 --> 21:36.220
What does that mean practically?

21:37.040 --> 21:41.000
Imagine the memory pointer drifting randomly left and right across the tape.

21:41.000 --> 21:53.660
Even though you cannot predict its absolute physical position at any given moment, its even or odd status is entirely deterministic based solely on the number of steps that is taken.

21:54.060 --> 21:57.260
Ah, so it's a foundational mathematical invariant.

21:57.380 --> 21:57.840
Exactly.

21:58.200 --> 22:05.060
You can always know the parity of the pointer by counting the operational steps, regardless of the chaos of its spatial location.

22:05.060 --> 22:06.880
This blew my mind.

22:06.880 --> 22:15.720
Which brings us to the sphere pot layer of the paper, where Flyxion introduces the concept of bubbles as met-to-stable attractors.

22:15.720 --> 22:16.200
Bubbles.

22:16.200 --> 22:21.600
Because you obviously can't just store a standard variable in a single memory cell on this random tape.

22:21.980 --> 22:24.520
The random drift would instantly destroy the value.

22:24.740 --> 22:26.040
It would be gone in a second.

22:26.200 --> 22:26.420
Right.

22:26.700 --> 22:28.580
So instead, you have to create a bubble.

22:28.720 --> 22:29.860
And a bubble isn't a variable.

22:30.220 --> 22:37.160
It is a localized probability distribution deliberately spaced out across the tape to respect that underlying parity constraint.

22:37.420 --> 22:42.560
And the mechanics of operating on this bubble are where the true metaphor for collective cognition emerges.

22:42.700 --> 22:43.640
Yeah, walk me through that.

22:43.640 --> 22:48.820
The paper outlines a minimal Python interpreter designed to interact with this chaos.

22:49.520 --> 22:51.020
First, you allocate a bubble.

22:51.540 --> 22:57.960
Then, you focus on it, which involves navigating the random pointer into the general vicinity of the distribution.

22:58.260 --> 22:59.540
Just getting close to it.

22:59.580 --> 22:59.760
Right.

22:59.920 --> 23:03.040
But to actually give it value, you have to jiggle it.

23:03.260 --> 23:03.900
Jiggle it.

23:04.040 --> 23:09.140
You stochasticly perturb the bubble to accumulate energy in the local field.

23:09.680 --> 23:13.140
And reading the data is the most fascinating part of all this.

23:13.140 --> 23:13.920
It really is.

23:13.980 --> 23:15.940
You don't just look at the bubble and read a number.

23:16.500 --> 23:17.860
You have to stabilize it.

23:18.520 --> 23:18.960
Stabilize.

23:19.020 --> 23:23.480
The stabilize function in the code snippet is essentially a statistical majority boat.

23:23.960 --> 23:26.980
The interpreter observes the bubble 101 times.

23:27.100 --> 23:28.200
A sample size of 101.

23:28.680 --> 23:29.140
Exactly.

23:29.920 --> 23:35.860
If there are more positive values than negative values in that sample size, the system agrees it is a positive bubble.

23:36.380 --> 23:37.520
If not, it is negative.

23:37.820 --> 23:38.520
But there's a catch?

23:38.720 --> 23:39.820
The mortality functional.

23:40.220 --> 23:40.560
Yes.

23:41.040 --> 23:42.120
The mortality functional.

23:42.120 --> 23:57.040
If you do not actively, continuously run this stabilized function, if you stop jiggling and voting on the bubble, the inherent random drift of the substrate will eventually dissolve the probability distribution back into pure noise.

23:57.040 --> 24:00.840
So if you don't actively govern the meaning, the meaning dies.

24:01.420 --> 24:06.080
It is a profound, mathematically grounded metaphor for meaning itself.

24:07.200 --> 24:11.460
Computation on this substrate is not the execution of a static, unyielding program.

24:11.580 --> 24:12.240
What is it then?

24:12.440 --> 24:18.600
It is the ongoing active governance of metastable attractors against the constant pressure of entropic drift.

24:18.600 --> 24:19.560
That is so deep.

24:19.640 --> 24:23.000
I keep visualizing this as trying to navigate a massive ship across the ocean.

24:23.280 --> 24:26.660
But the steering wheel is broken and randomly spins left or right on its own.

24:26.740 --> 24:27.900
You cannot rely on the wheel.

24:28.000 --> 24:28.260
Right.

24:28.480 --> 24:35.120
But you can still cross the ocean successfully if you rely on the stars, which represent the undeniable invariant of parity.

24:35.580 --> 24:41.720
And if you constantly take navigational readings and mathematically correct your course, which is the stabilization loop.

24:41.940 --> 24:43.140
That's a fantastic analogy.

24:43.360 --> 24:46.680
And if we connect this esoteric thought experiment back to the bigger picture.

24:46.680 --> 24:48.120
The whole GitHub ecosystem?

24:48.620 --> 24:48.940
Right.

24:49.920 --> 24:57.780
Embistro proves that semantic meaning survives through statistical semantic persistence, not through perfect, rigid, symbolic rules.

24:57.920 --> 25:00.800
Which maps perfectly onto the open source ecosystem.

25:01.100 --> 25:01.720
Exactly.

25:02.160 --> 25:04.240
GitHub is a chaotic environment.

25:04.880 --> 25:12.020
It is filled with broken code, deprecated dependencies, abandoned projects, platform shifts, and noisy human arguments.

25:12.120 --> 25:12.680
Constant noise.

25:12.680 --> 25:18.000
Yet, the meaning and utility of the global software stack survives and grows.

25:18.460 --> 25:18.720
Why?

25:19.140 --> 25:24.620
Because the collective ecosystem is constantly forking, patching, and stabilizing those repositories.

25:24.720 --> 25:27.360
The human developers are the stabilization function.

25:27.560 --> 25:28.900
They are the ones jiggling and voting.

25:29.340 --> 25:29.560
Okay.

25:29.700 --> 25:32.020
This is a beautiful philosophical framework.

25:32.020 --> 25:39.400
But if meaning survives through this chaotic statistical persistence, we have a very practical problem for AI.

25:39.820 --> 25:40.360
Oh, absolutely.

25:40.620 --> 25:49.420
How does a generative algorithm looking at GitHub know the difference between useful, recoverable code that just needs a little stabilization and absolute, irrecoverable garbage?

25:49.540 --> 25:52.780
Because if it's a random walk, how does it know which way is forward?

25:52.780 --> 25:53.540
Exactly.

25:53.960 --> 25:56.500
That is the core of the admissibility problem.

25:57.000 --> 26:05.240
And Flyxion addresses this by defining three tiers of admissibility, establishing exactly what constitutes viable training data for an AI.

26:05.500 --> 26:08.740
These tiers are based on the concept of admissible replay structure.

26:08.960 --> 26:10.140
Admissible replay structure.

26:10.580 --> 26:17.600
And this is where the paper completely upends a massive assumption in machine learning regarding data quality and Shannon entropy.

26:17.880 --> 26:18.160
Yes.

26:18.320 --> 26:21.300
We need to define Shannon entropy carefully here for the listener.

26:21.460 --> 26:21.760
Go ahead.

26:21.760 --> 26:28.560
In information theory, Shannon entropy is a measure of the unpredictability or information density of a data source.

26:28.960 --> 26:29.560
Unpredictability.

26:29.700 --> 26:29.880
Right.

26:30.220 --> 26:35.880
A file containing perfectly random static has maximum Shannon entropy because every bit is unpredictable.

26:36.380 --> 26:37.680
You literally cannot compress it.

26:38.140 --> 26:38.380
Okay.

26:38.540 --> 26:44.720
But a file containing the same letter A repeated a million times has near zero Shannon entropy.

26:44.840 --> 26:45.020
Right.

26:45.020 --> 26:51.620
So a lot of naive data scraping approaches assume that high information density, high Shannon entropy equals high value for training.

26:51.760 --> 26:57.680
Like if I see it in AI, a massive file of highly complex, dense data, it should learn more, right?

26:57.680 --> 27:05.300
It seems logical, but the paper proves mathematically that Shannon entropy and admissible replay structure are statistically independent.

27:05.600 --> 27:06.560
Totally unrelated.

27:06.560 --> 27:08.080
This is a crucial distinction.

27:08.720 --> 27:10.900
Let's look at the three tiers to understand why.

27:10.980 --> 27:11.420
Let's do it.

27:11.500 --> 27:11.920
Tier one.

27:12.100 --> 27:16.800
Tier one comprises well-formed repositories with stable semantic normal forms.

27:17.340 --> 27:18.240
These are the gold standard.

27:18.420 --> 27:19.400
The perfect code.

27:19.580 --> 27:19.820
Right.

27:20.300 --> 27:22.420
The code base is functionally robust.

27:22.420 --> 27:29.340
Every architectural design decision is clearly documented, and the developmental trajectory is fully mathematically recoverable.

27:29.700 --> 27:37.120
So when an LLM ingests a tier one repository, it learns the precise geometry of perfect procedural reasoning.

27:37.320 --> 27:37.700
Exactly.

27:38.340 --> 27:40.560
But tier two is where the magic actually happens.

27:40.820 --> 27:41.680
The broken code.

27:41.960 --> 27:42.240
Yes.

27:42.780 --> 27:44.180
Tier two repositories are broken.

27:44.560 --> 27:45.340
They do not work.

27:45.340 --> 27:48.700
But they contain recoverable architectural intent.

27:49.200 --> 27:50.780
Recoverable architectural intent.

27:50.960 --> 27:55.560
This is the web scraper we talked about earlier that failed because of an off-by-one indexing error.

27:55.960 --> 27:56.440
Precisely.

27:56.800 --> 28:02.460
The code won't compile or it throws an exception, but the underlying logical structure is fundamentally sound.

28:02.780 --> 28:06.440
You can see the ghost of what the human developer was trying to achieve.

28:06.760 --> 28:07.040
Yes.

28:07.580 --> 28:08.800
And then there's tier three.

28:09.420 --> 28:12.460
These are uploads with absolutely no recoverable structure.

28:12.560 --> 28:13.020
Garbage.

28:13.020 --> 28:23.520
Imagine a repository where someone accidentally committed a compiled binary file, or a massive dump of randomized cryptographic keys, or literally just white noise.

28:23.640 --> 28:26.880
This is where the Shannon entropy trap becomes super obvious.

28:27.400 --> 28:32.440
Because that tier three file of randomized cryptographic keys has maximum Shannon entropy.

28:32.780 --> 28:35.340
It is incredibly dense with data.

28:35.480 --> 28:37.040
But it has zero architectural intent.

28:37.120 --> 28:37.440
Zero.

28:37.440 --> 28:40.420
There is no developmental geometry to recover.

28:41.000 --> 28:47.940
No sequence of human problem solving led to that random string in a way that an AI can generalize to write a new software application.

28:47.940 --> 28:55.780
So if you filter your AI training data purely by looking for high information density, you are poisoning your model with random static.

28:56.080 --> 28:57.880
You are feeding it tier three garbage.

28:58.120 --> 28:58.500
Exactly.

28:59.100 --> 29:02.020
Generative algorithms do not simply memorize the text of files.

29:02.320 --> 29:04.200
This is the biggest misconception about LLMs.

29:04.320 --> 29:05.380
They aren't just copy-pasting.

29:05.380 --> 29:13.940
When an advanced model ingests a tier two repository, that broken code base with the indexing error, it does not learn to write broken code.

29:13.940 --> 29:23.040
It correlates that broken trajectory with thousands of other similar trajectories it has seen that did eventually reach a tier one state.

29:23.600 --> 29:24.520
It learns the vector.

29:25.320 --> 29:30.140
It learns that the failed tier two code base was attempting to become a tier one code base.

29:30.140 --> 29:34.900
And it learns the specific geometric pathway required to bridge that gap.

29:35.260 --> 29:36.760
The AI isn't learning the mistake.

29:37.000 --> 29:38.840
It's learning the trajectory of correction.

29:39.040 --> 29:40.260
It learns how to fix things.

29:40.520 --> 29:42.720
But here is a deeply mechanical question.

29:43.280 --> 29:52.620
How exactly does a system like Git mathematically record this trajectory so that an AI or a human can actually read the exact sequence of events?

29:52.840 --> 29:53.560
The timeline.

29:53.560 --> 30:00.480
Right. How do we establish the arrow of time in a decentralized network where millions of people are coding simultaneously on different computers?

30:01.200 --> 30:03.660
The answer lies in the cryptography of the commit hash.

30:04.300 --> 30:10.560
Flyxion connects the Git commit hash to a foundational concept in computer science called Lamport timestamps.

30:11.280 --> 30:16.260
Let's break down the physics of time in a distributed system because this part is just wild to me.

30:16.260 --> 30:16.740
It's wild.

30:16.880 --> 30:21.500
If I am coding in Tokyo and you are coding in New York, our laptop clocks are never perfectly sync.

30:21.600 --> 30:22.180
Never perfect.

30:22.180 --> 30:32.440
If we both push code to a project at roughly the exact same moment, how does the system know whose code came first without relying on a centralized master server to stamp the time?

30:32.580 --> 30:37.260
Well, in 1978, Leslie Lamport published a seminal paper on logical clocks.

30:37.460 --> 30:38.820
1978? Wow.

30:38.960 --> 30:44.360
He realized that in a distributed network, absolute chronological time is an illusion.

30:44.540 --> 30:45.020
An illusion.

30:45.300 --> 30:48.080
You don't need to know the exact atomic time an event occurred.

30:48.300 --> 30:52.060
You only need to know its causal relationship to other events.

30:52.180 --> 30:53.040
Causality.

30:53.460 --> 30:53.700
Right.

30:54.020 --> 31:01.060
If event A causes event B, then event A mathematically must have a smaller logical timestamp than event B.

31:01.200 --> 31:01.360
Yeah.

31:01.680 --> 31:04.980
Time is defined by causality, not by a clock on the wall.

31:04.980 --> 31:10.740
And Lennis Torvalds fundamentally embedded this concept into Git when he invented it in 2005.

31:11.060 --> 31:11.320
He did.

31:11.540 --> 31:14.480
When you commit a piece of code, Git doesn't just save the file.

31:14.480 --> 31:20.780
It generates a cryptographic hash, specifically a SHA-1 hash, that acts as a digital fingerprint.

31:21.020 --> 31:23.680
But that hash doesn't just fingerprint your new code.

31:23.860 --> 31:24.000
Yeah.

31:24.100 --> 31:26.860
It mathematically incorporates the hash of the previous commit.

31:27.160 --> 31:27.600
Exactly.

31:27.940 --> 31:34.620
And that previous commit incorporated the hash of the one before it, stretching all the way back to the very inception of the repository.

31:34.620 --> 31:43.680
So a single Git commit hash encodes the complete, unbroken, causal history of that project up to that exact microsecond.

31:43.760 --> 31:47.580
It locks the sequence of events into a mathematically undeniable chain.

31:47.980 --> 31:53.320
Every time a programmer commits a change, they are applying an irreversible constraint to the project.

31:53.960 --> 31:58.060
They are permanently narrowing the universe of possible futures for that software.

31:58.060 --> 32:07.060
If we recall our discussion of the chaotic S-long embassies, where parity was the minimal mathematical invariant that survived random noise.

32:07.760 --> 32:11.980
Git commit hashes are the parity bits of the global software ecosystem.

32:12.060 --> 32:13.220
Oh, that's a great connection.

32:13.520 --> 32:23.960
They are the minimal structural invariants that survived the deeply asynchronous, chaotic, unpredictable process of thousands of humans working on the exact same code base.

32:23.960 --> 32:28.560
I think about all the mundane administrative tasks developers do every single day.

32:28.660 --> 32:29.620
Writing commit messages?

32:29.980 --> 32:30.240
Right.

32:30.920 --> 32:34.860
Arguing and issue threads, resolving merge conflicts and pull requests.

32:35.400 --> 32:38.440
We view all of that as just bureaucratic friction.

32:38.740 --> 32:41.300
Just the annoying human costs of doing business.

32:41.620 --> 32:51.880
But Flyxion is arguing that these exact artifacts, the arguments, the merge resolutions, the commit histories, they are the primary carriers of developmental structure.

32:51.880 --> 32:57.140
They are the externalized reasoning of the human species locked into a causal chain.

32:57.360 --> 32:57.800
Exactly.

32:58.020 --> 33:00.860
A snapshot of code just tells you what the machine is doing.

33:01.380 --> 33:04.760
The causal commit history tells you why the human told the machine to do it.

33:04.880 --> 33:06.560
This brings us to the ultimate synthesis.

33:06.820 --> 33:07.300
Yes, it does.

33:07.440 --> 33:20.020
Because now that we deeply understand the mechanics of the substrate, that it is a mathematically sound, causally locked library of human trajectories, failures, and architectural intent, we can finally ask the biggest question of all.

33:20.300 --> 33:21.360
What's the AI doing?

33:21.360 --> 33:21.960
Right.

33:22.360 --> 33:30.460
When you open an interface and prompt a generative AI to write code for you, what is the algorithm actually doing inside this massive graph?

33:30.540 --> 33:35.720
Because we firmly established it isn't just regurgitating Python syntax rules it memorized from a textbook.

33:35.840 --> 33:37.640
No, it's doing something much more profound.

33:38.100 --> 33:43.960
Flyxion defines large language models in this context as manifold compression operators.

33:44.120 --> 33:45.580
Manifold compression operators.

33:45.680 --> 33:50.040
Okay, we need to define what a manifold is in topology to make sense of that term.

33:50.040 --> 33:50.260
Sure.

33:50.740 --> 33:57.060
Think of the entire global graph of GitHub repositories as a high-dimensional space of procedural knowledge.

33:57.240 --> 33:58.220
Okay, high-dimensional.

33:58.420 --> 34:06.820
Every repository, every fork, every commit is a point in this massive, multi-dimensional configuration space.

34:06.880 --> 34:07.740
It's huge.

34:07.740 --> 34:19.940
It is globally accessible and it is theoretically searchable, but by the late 2010s, this space had become too vast, too impossibly complex for any human mind to navigate efficiently.

34:19.940 --> 34:25.460
You couldn't just use a keyword search to find the perfect architectural solution to a complex systemic problem.

34:25.600 --> 34:26.400
It's just too big.

34:26.500 --> 34:26.940
Exactly.

34:27.140 --> 34:36.020
So what a large language model does during training is compress this impossibly huge, high-dimensional space into a lower-dimensional space, a manifold.

34:36.260 --> 34:37.060
It compresses it.

34:37.060 --> 34:44.600
It maps the relationships, the distances, and the semantic connections between all these different developmental trajectories so it can be navigated mathematically.

34:44.860 --> 34:46.460
Here's where it gets really interesting.

34:46.780 --> 34:57.580
When you sit down at your laptop today and type a prompt saying, you know, write a Python script to authenticate with this specific API and parse the JSON response into a database.

